Phase 3 – Model Testing and Performance Evaluation

Project Title:
Diabetes Risk Prediction using Machine Learning

Objective:
The objective of this phase is to evaluate and compare the performance of multiple machine learning models for accurate diabetes risk prediction using
different evaluation metrics and visualization techniques.

Description:
In this phase, the project focuses on testing and evaluating the trained machine learning models using the preprocessed diabetes dataset. The 
dataset is provided to multiple classification algorithms including Logistic Regression, K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN), Decision Tree, and Support 
Vector Machine (SVM) to analyze their prediction performance.
The models are evaluated using important classification metrics such as Accuracy, Precision, Recall, and F1-Score to measure reliability and 
effectiveness in predicting diabetes risk. Confusion matrices are generated to visualize correct and incorrect predictions made by each model.
Additional visualizations and comparisons are performed to understand the strengths and weaknesses of different algorithms.
This phase helps identify the most suitable model for diabetes prediction by comparing the performance of all implemented algorithms on the testing dataset.

Tasks Completed:
Model testing using trained datasets
Performance evaluation of Logistic Regression
Performance evaluation of K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
Performance evaluation of Decision Tree
Performance evaluation of Support Vector Machine (SVM)
Calculation of Accuracy, Precision, Recall, and F1-Score
Confusion matrix generation and analysis
Model comparison and result interpretation
Output visualization and performance analysis

Tools & Technologies Used:
Python
Pandas
NumPy
Matplotlib / Seaborn
Scikit-learn
Files Included:
db_risk.csv – Preprocessed dataset
PBL_notebook.ipynb – Model testing and evaluation code
Output Screenshots – Accuracy results, confusion matrices, and evaluation outputs

Outcome of Phase-3:
The machine learning models are successfully tested and evaluated using multiple performance metrics. Comparative analysis of 
Logistic Regression, KNN, Decision Tree, and SVM is completed to identify the most accurate and reliable model for diabetes risk prediction. 
The final system is now capable of predicting whether a patient is diabetic or non-diabetic based on clinical health parameters.M
